From: jwinstea@jarthur.claremont.edu (Jim Winstead Jr.)
Newsgroups: alt.os.linux
Subject: Re: 'combeg.dos' (DOS) Beginner's Guide...(commands)(1st draft)
Date: 19 Mar 92 05:55:58 GMT
Organization: Harvey Mudd College, WIBSTR

In article <3977@sumax.seattleu.edu> boyer@sumax.seattleu.edu (Chuck Boyer) writes:
>These are executables, called 'binaries' in the unix environment
>which
>are kept in the directory '/usr/bin' in Linux;

You need to look over and make sure you've identified them in the
right place - some of them moved from 0.95 to 0.95a.  I've tried to
note those below.

>bison <--- part of GNU
	parser generator (yacc replacement)

>cat   <--- two definitions/uses; lists files to screen that already
	in /bin now.

>chown
	change owner of a file

>comm
	compare two sorted files line-by-line

>cp    <--- copy a file to; (user defined/supplied new filename,
	in /bin now.

>csplit
	split a file into sections determined by context lines

>dd
	convert a file while copying it (?)

>dhrystone
	benchmarking software

>doshell
	this has been superceded by init/getty/login.

>du
	summarize disk usage

>egrep
	print lines matching a regular expression (extended grep)

>em    <--- GNU micro-emacs, editor
	this isn't GNU.  Just MicroEMACS.

>expand
	convert tabs to spaces

>fiz
	fix zoo archives

>flex
	(fast) lexical analyzer

>fold
	wrap each input line to fit in a specified width

>join
	join lines of two files on a common field

>lesskey
	setup keys for less

>ln    <--- link a file in one directory to be in the current
>directory,
>             without actually having to copy it.
	or link to another name (i.e. compress -> uncompress)

>mkfifo
	make a FIFO (not implemented?)

>mkfs  <--- make a file system. Format a partition or disk for
>Linux.
	this doesn't really format a partition, it just prepares it
	for use by Linux.  now in /bin

>mv  <---- move a file from where it is to another location/name.
	in /bin

>od
	octal dump - dump a file to stdout in octal form

>paste
	merge lines of files

>rm   <--- remove a file.
>rmdir <-- remove a directory.
	both in /bin

>sed
	stream editor

>ship
	prepare shar files (I think)

>sort
	sort lines of text files

>split
	split a file into pieces

>stty
	change and print terminal line settings

>sum
	checksum and count the blocks in a file

>tac
	concatenate and print files in reverse (cat backwards - get it?)

>tar  <--- compress/shrink a file/directorys
	in /bin

>uncompress <--- expand a shrunken file to its original size.
	linked to compress, in /bin

>unexpand
	convert spaces to tabs

>uniq
	remove duplicate lines from a sorted file

>updatedb
	update the locate database


>located in /dev;

>PS0 is the device of floppy drive a:, 1.2M in PS/2 systems
>PS1 is the device name of floppy drive b:, 1.4M in PS/2 systems.
>at0 is the device name of floppy drive a:, 1.2 in at clones.
at1 is the device name of floppy drive b:, 1.2 in at clones

>this is the usual Unix, Minix, Linux 0.12 operating systems.
>Linux 0.95 has differend names;

You should eliminate the hd[0-9] stuff, it's irrelevant and confusing.

>(these are the 1st draft of these instructions, there will
>definately be more continuity and further instructions by the
>second draft, about 2 weeks from today, eg.; 4/8/92).

Some comments:

-	things should probably be lined up better (use tabs!) so it
	reads a little easier.

-	I'm not quite sure what the point is.  What you have now is
	primarily a dump of the /usr/man/whatis file.

	I think you should work on expanding the descriptions to a few
	lines apiece, and show the relation between DOS commands like
	copy, delete, etc and the Linux commands.

(Sorry if any of this sounds too bossy - I'm just trying to throw some
thoughts at you....)
-- 
